# W1': a `|>` chain directly after a value-position js"…" literal (the DQUOTE
# escape-hatch delimiter — this case deliberately pins the dquote+js corner
# of the lang x delimiter matrix; the parser unit matrix covers all six) in a
# `{{ }}` Go block. Unlike an `{ }` interpolation, a GoBlock has no top-level
# pipe grammar of its own (Code is plain Go statement text, never run through
# parsePipe's stage-stripping), so this fires on ANY literal directly
# followed by `|>` in a block, not just one nested inside a larger
# expression. Caught at parse time, positioned at the `|>`, instead of the
# generic, unpositioned "expected operand, found '>'" the same broken
# statement text would otherwise hit once the assembled skeleton is parsed as
# Go (contrast element_rejected.txtar in this same dir, whose rejection is a
# later, analyze-time diagnostic — this one is a parse error, so the render
# facet never runs).
-- input.gsx --
package demo

component Page() {
	{{ h := js"f()" |> minify }}
	<p>done</p>
}
-- invoke --
Page()
-- diagnostics.golden --
4:18: whole-literal pipelines are not supported in Go-expression position; wrap the literal in a function call instead
-- render.golden --
